<html>
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>Catheterization Theory &amp; Techniques</title>
    <link href="Case_sheet_styles.css" rel="stylesheet">
    <script src="https://www.youtube.com/iframe_api"></script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/kMNURM6go2M"

        title="Catheterization: Theory &amp; Techniques | PLAB2/UKMLA" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"

        referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="" height="773"

        frameborder="0" width="1414"></iframe> </div>
    <h3>URINARY CATHETERIZATION: PROCEDURE AND MANAGEMENT OVERVIEW</h3>
    <h4>A. GENERAL PRINCIPLES &amp; PREPARATION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=34s">Video
        0:34</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Sterility is paramount:</strong> This is a sterile procedure,
        and maintaining sterility throughout is crucial. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=37s">Video
          0:37-0:45</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Equipment:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Ensure all necessary items are ready. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=34s">Video
              0:34-0:36</a>)</li>
          <li>Catheterization kits are often pre-packed with all instruments.
            (Unlike blood sampling where items might be gathered individually).
            (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=50s">Video
              0:50-1:17</a>)</li>
          <li>Essential items (as shown on slide at <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=22s">0:22</a>):
            <ul>
              <li>See next video</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Patient Communication &amp; Consent:</strong> (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=81s">Video
          1:21</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Explain the procedure: "I am going to put a catheter, which is a
            thin plastic tube, through your penis into your bladder to help
            drain the urine." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=83s">Video
              1:23-1:29</a>)</li>
          <li>Explain the need for exposure: "For this examination, I would like
            you to undress below your waist." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=91s">Video
              1:31-1:34</a>)</li>
          <li>Offer a chaperone and ensure privacy. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=94s">Video
              1:34-1:35</a>)</li>
          <li>Obtain verbal consent: "May I proceed?" (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=95s">Video
              1:35-1:36</a>)</li>
          <li>Advise the patient they can ask to stop at any time if
            uncomfortable. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=97s">Video
              1:37-1:41</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>B. CONTRAINDICATIONS FOR FOLEY'S CATHETER (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=103s">Video
        1:43</a>)</h4>
    <p><em>It's crucial to rule out contraindications before attempting Foley
        catheterization.</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=149s">Video
        2:29-2:35</a>)</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Recent urethral instrumentation.</strong> (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=115s">Video
          1:55-1:56</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Blood at the tip of the penis (meatal blood):</strong> This
        can be a sign of pelvic trauma/urethral injury. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=118s">Video
          1:58-2:09</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Recent trauma</strong> (especially pelvic trauma). (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=123s">Video
          2:03, referenced with blood at meatus</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Scrotal haematoma:</strong> This can also indicate pelvic
        trauma. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=134s">Video
          2:14-2:16</a>)</li>
      <li><em>If contraindications are present, a <strong>suprapubic
            catheterization</strong> might be considered instead.</em> (<a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=140s">Video
          2:20-2:23</a>)</li>
    </ul>
    <h4>C. PATIENT SCENARIO: ACUTE URINARY RETENTION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=157s">Video
        2:37</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Patient Details:</strong> George Jefferson, 55 years old (age
        updated by presenter from 45). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=160s">Video
          2:40-2:43</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>Presenting Complaint:</strong> Lower abdominal
        discomfort/severe suprapubic pain. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=165s">Video
          2:45-2:50</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=200s">3:20</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>Pain started 1 hour ago, is getting worse, rated 9/10. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=203s">Video
              3:23-3:33</a>)</li>
          <li>Unable to pass urine for the last 24 hours. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=215s">Video
              3:35-3:46</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Initial Assessment &amp; Diagnosis:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>History taking (brief, as patient is in severe pain). (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=187s">Video
              3:07</a>)</li>
          <li>Abdominal Examination (findings often provided by examiner in
            simulation):
            <ul>
              <li>Tenderness in the suprapubic area. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=310s">Video
                  5:10-5:21</a>)</li>
              <li>Bladder is palpable and full. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=323s">Video
                  5:23-5:29</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Working Diagnosis:</strong> Acute Urinary Retention. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=230s">Video
              3:50</a>, <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=332s">5:32</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>D. MANAGEMENT STEPS FOR ACUTE URINARY RETENTION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=290s">Video
        4:50</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Immediate Management &amp; Communication:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Prioritize relieving the retention, especially if the patient is
            in severe pain. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=257s">Video
              4:17-4:28</a>)</li>
          <li>Inform the patient about the diagnosis of urinary retention. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=332s">Video
              5:32</a>)</li>
          <li>Explain that the treatment is to insert a Foley's catheter. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=337s">Video
              5:37-5:42</a>)</li>
          <li>Briefly explain the catheterization procedure: cleaning the area,
            using anaesthetic gel, inserting the tube. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=348s">Video
              5:48-5:56</a>)</li>
          <li>Reiterate consent, privacy, offer of a chaperone, and the
            patient's right to stop the procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=356s">Video
              5:56-6:06</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Catheterization Procedure Highlights:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Perform the Foleys using a sterile technique. (This is the
            "relevant procedure" mentioned in the task at <a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=182s">3:02</a>).</li>
          <li>Ensure contraindications have been checked and are not present. (<a

              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=376s">Video
              6:16-6:19</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Further History &amp; Investigations (Post-Relief or in
          parallel if patient is comfortable):</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Inquire about symptoms suggestive of BPH using the <strong>FUNWISE</strong>
            mnemonic (Frequency, Urgency, Nocturia, Weak stream, Intermittency,
            Straining, Emptying incomplete). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=22s">Slide
              at 0:22</a>, discussed around <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=438s">7:18-7:38</a>)</li>
          <li>Ask about symptoms of UTI or any cancer red flags (e.g.,
            haematuria, weight loss - often negative in exam scenarios). (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=461s">Video
              7:41-7:49</a>)</li>
          <li>Perform/discuss Digital Rectal Examination (DRE): In this
            scenario, the examiner might provide findings like "both lobes of
            the prostate are enlarged but smooth." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=485s">Video
              8:05-8:24</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Post-Catheterization Management &amp; Follow-Up Plan:</strong>
        (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=511s">Video
          8:31</a>)
        <ul>
          <li>The patient may require initial observation in the hospital. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=514s">Video
              8:34-8:36</a>)</li>
          <li>The patient can be sent home with the catheter in situ. (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=534s">Video
              8:54-8:58</a>)</li>
          <li>Provide education on managing the catheter bag (e.g., how to
            change it). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=540s">Video
              9:00-9:04</a>)</li>
          <li>Arrange follow-up in an outpatient clinic, typically in about 2
            weeks. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=545s">Video
              9:05-9:12</a>)</li>
          <li>Plan for a Trial Without Catheter (TWOC) at the follow-up
            appointment. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=556s">Video
              9:16-9:19</a>)</li>
          <li>Assess residual urine volume (e.g., via ultrasound) after TWOC. (<a

              class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=560s">Video
              9:20-9:23</a>)</li>
          <li>Discuss definitive treatment for the underlying cause (e.g., if
            BPH, medications like Tamsulosin or Finasteride). (<a class="timestamp"

              href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=567s">Video
              9:27-9:36</a>)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><em><b>Note:</b> The main goal in an acute urinary retention scenario is
        to relieve the obstruction via catheterization safely and then to
        investigate and manage the underlying cause.</em> (<a class="timestamp"

        href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kMNURM6go2M&amp;t=645s">Video
        10:45-10:52</a>)</p>




    <h3>URINARY CATHETERIZATION: MALE FOLEY CATHETER PROCEDURE</h3>

    <div class="video-container">
        <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/L2AQMNL0Oow"
        title="Urinary Catheterisation - OSCE Video - "
        allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
        referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen=""
        frameborder="0"></iframe>
    </div>

    <h4>A. PRE-PROCEDURAL STEPS & COMMUNICATION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=9s">Video 0:09</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Rule out Contraindications:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=10s">Video 0:10-0:28</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Ask about recent trauma. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=15s">Video 0:15-0:17</a>)</li>
                <li>Check for scrotal hematoma. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=17s">Video 0:17-0:20</a>)</li>
                <li>Check for bleeding from the external urethral meatus. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=20s">Video 0:20-0:21</a>)</li>
                <li>Ask about any recent instrumentation. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=24s">Video 0:24-0:26</a>)</li>
                <li><em>If contraindications are present, Foley catheterization may not be appropriate, and suprapubic catheterization might be considered.</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=28s">Video 0:28-0:33</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Explain Procedure to Patient:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=35s">Video 0:35-0:53</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>"I am going to put a thin flexible tube in your bladder through your penis in order to relieve the symptoms/get the urine output." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=42s">Video 0:42-0:51</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Exposure, Chaperone, and Consent:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=38s">Video 0:38-0:41</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Ask patient to undress below the waist. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=53s">Video 0:53-0:55</a>)</li>
                <li>Offer and ensure a chaperone is present for privacy. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=58s">Video 0:58-0:59</a>)</li>
                <li>Obtain verbal consent.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Patient Positioning and Comfort:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=59s">Video 0:59-1:03</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Tell the patient to lie down comfortably on the bed with legs slightly apart. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=61s">Video 1:01-1:03</a>)</li>
                <li>Address pain concerns: "We'll be using a numbing agent (anaesthetic jelly) to make sure the procedure is not going to be painful." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=66s">Video 1:06-1:14</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>B. EQUIPMENT CHECK & PREPARATION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=77s">Video 1:17</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Mannequin/Patient Preparation:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Ensure the mannequin (or patient) is draped if not already. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=80s">Video 1:20-1:26</a>)</li>
                <li>Perform this step while gloved. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=86s">Video 1:26-1:28</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Gathered Equipment:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Sterile gloves.</li>
                <li>kidney trays.</li>
                <li>Sterile drape.</li>
                <li>Antiseptic solution/normal saline.</li>
                <li>Sterile water (for balloon). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=91s">Video 1:31</a>)</li>
                <li>Normal saline (for cleaning). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=92s">Video 1:32</a>)</li>
                <li>Anaesthetic gel. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=95s">Video 1:35</a>)</li>
                <li>Forceps. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=98s">Video 1:38</a>)</li>
                <li>Two syringes (one for anaesthetic jelly, one for sterile water). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=100s">Video 1:40-1:46</a>)</li>
                <li>Gauze pieces. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=106s">Video 1:46</a>)</li>
                <li>Catheter. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=110s">Video 1:50</a>)</li>
                <li>Urine bag. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=118s">Video 1:58</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Catheter Handling (if new):</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=121s">Video 2:01</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Open using non-touch technique, maintaining sterility of the catheter inside. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=126s">Video 2:06-2:13</a>)</li>
                <li>A staff member can assist with opening if available. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=140s">Video 2:20-2:25</a>)</li>
                <li>Drop the catheter into the sterile field (kidney dish). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=150s">Video 2:30-2:33</a>)</li>
                <li>Dispose of outer packaging. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=157s">Video 2:37-2:40</a>)</li>
                <li>Remove protective covering from the catheter tip just before use (while gloved). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=173s">Video 2:53-2:58</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>C. STERILE PROCEDURE: CLEANING & JELLY APPLICATION (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=181s">Video 3:01</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Cleaning the Penis:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=186s">Video 3:06-3:09</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Use forceps and gauze. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=184s">Video 3:04</a>)</li>
                <li>Clean the penis, typically three times. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=189s">Video 3:09-3:12</a>)</li>
                <li>Dip gauze in normal saline or antiseptic solution. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=195s">Video 3:15-3:21</a>)</li>
                <li>Discard used gauze in the waste area after each wipe. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=203s">Video 3:23, 3:26, 3:37</a>)</li>
                <li>Dispose of forceps after cleaning. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=228s">Video 3:48</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Change Gloves (Optional but good practice):</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=234s">Video 3:54-3:56</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>After cleaning, consider changing to a new pair of sterile gloves.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Anaesthetic Jelly Application:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=240s">Video 4:00</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Fill a syringe with anaesthetic jelly. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=242s">Video 4:02-4:05</a>)</li>
                <li>Warn the patient: "I'm going to put the anaesthetic jelly, you might feel a sting or a cold sensation." (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=245s">Video 4:05-4:13</a>)</li>
                <li>Instill the jelly into the urethra.</li>
                <li>Advise waiting for a minute or two for the jelly to take effect. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=258s">Video 4:18-4:24</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>D. CATHETER INSERTION & SECUREMENT (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=268s">Video 4:28</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Catheter Insertion:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Warn the patient before insertion. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=272s">Video 4:32-4:39</a>)</li>
                <li>Gently insert the catheter into the urethral meatus.</li>
                <li>Simultaneously pull back the protective catheter cover as you advance the catheter. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=284s">Video 4:44-4:52</a>)</li>
                <li>Insert the catheter fully (up to the bifurcation/Y-junction). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=298s">Video 4:58-5:02</a>)</li>
                <li>Observe for urine flow into the catheter/bag. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=311s">Video 5:11-5:14</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Balloon Inflation:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=314s">Video 5:14</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Use the pre-filled syringe with sterile water (typically 10ml, but check catheter instructions). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=318s">Video 5:18-5:24</a>)</li>
                <li>Inflate the balloon via the designated port.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Confirm Placement & Secure:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Gently tug the catheter slightly to ensure the balloon is seated at the bladder neck. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=325s">Video 5:25-5:31</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Attach Urine Bag:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=331s">Video 5:31-5:37</a>)
            <ul>
                <li>Securely connect the urine drainage bag to the catheter.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>E. POST-PROCEDURAL STEPS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=341s">Video 5:41</a>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Observations:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Note the color and amount of urine. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=341s">Video 5:41-5:46</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Documentation & Bag Placement:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Record patient details on the bag/chart. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=346s">Video 5:46-5:47</a>)</li>
                <li>Hang the urine bag on the side of the patient's bed, below the level of the bladder. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=347s">Video 5:47-5:50</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Clean Up:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Dispose of all waste appropriately (clear the tray). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=350s">Video 5:50-5:56</a>)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Thank Patient.</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2AQMNL0Oow&t=356s">Video 5:56</a>)</li>
    </ul>





